  "chunk_index": 22,
  "summary": "While visiting the ailing Mrs. Clarke, Poirot and Hastings learn a significant detail that contradicts previous testimonies. Mrs. Clarke accuses Tora Grey of lying, claiming she personally witnessed the girl speaking to a poorly dressed stranger on the front steps at eleven o'clock on the morning of Mr. Clarke's death. This directly opposes Miss Grey's earlier claim that no strangers had visited the house. During their return to London, Poirot reflects on the various family dramas connected to the case, including the lives of the Anders, Bexhill, and Cheshire families.\n\nUpon arriving at White's Court, Poirot and Hastings are visited by Donald Fraser, who appears extremely nervous and prone to stuttering. Fraser confesses that he has been plagued by recurring, vivid dreams for three consecutive nights. In these dreams, he is on a beach searching for a girl named Betty; he finds her, but then proceeds to strangle her with a belt. He describes the horror of realizing the girl's face is actually Megan's. A distressed Fraser asks Poirot if these dreams imply he is a killer.\n\nThe conversation is interrupted by the arrival of a fourth letter. The message mocks the police and Poirot for their inability to solve the case. The letter provides a cryptic clue, stating that the letter \"T\" is still far away, and announces that the next event will occur on September 11th in Doncaster. The letter is signed \"ABC.\"",
